# Kernel and Jensen Diagnostics Checkpoint

## Project Context

This note consolidates the kernel-side diagnostics and finite Jensen polynomial tests performed during the current proof-development phase.

The working kernel convention is

\[
\Phi(u)
=
\sum_{n\ge 1}
\left(
2\pi^2 n^4 e^{9u}
-
3\pi n^2 e^{5u}
\right)
e^{-\pi n^2 e^{4u}},
\qquad
\Phi(-u)=\Phi(u).
\]

For positive deformation parameter \(\lambda\), the tested deformed kernel is

\[
\Phi_\lambda(u)=e^{\lambda u^2}\Phi(u).
\]

The associated even moments are

\[
M_k(\lambda)
=
\int_{\mathbb R} u^{2k}\Phi_\lambda(u)\,du,
\]

and the Jensen coefficient sequence is

\[
A_k(\lambda)
=
\frac{M_k(\lambda)k!}{(2k)!}.
\]

Finite Jensen polynomials are tested in the form

\[
P_{d,n}(x)
=
\sum_{k=0}^{d}
\binom{d}{k} A_{n+k} x^k.
\]

Equivalently,

\[
Q_{d,n}(y)=P_{d,n}(-y).
\]

The Jensen hyperbolicity test used here is:

\[
P_{d,n}(x)
\text{ has } d \text{ real nonpositive roots}
\iff
Q_{d,n}(y)
\text{ has } d \text{ positive real roots}.
\]

The final high-degree audits use Sturm root counting on \(Q_{d,n}(y)\), rather than floating-point polynomial root classification.

